<br>
Queen Rhiannon made her daily trek to the Meeting Hall,  where she met Queen Chiara for her lessons.<br>
She'd had no idea when she'd signed on for the job that there would be so much involved, so much she still needed to learn. Besides learning the customs of the tribe and the names of her athelfi, she had also had to study Amazon law and train with weaponry.<br>
As she approached the door, she was feeling a mix of excitement and dread. She wondered what Chiara had in store for her today.<br>
Taking a deep breath, Rhiannon entered. <br>
Chiara recognized that she intimidated Rhiannon at times, but considered it part of the girl's training to learn to say what needed to be said anyway.  She looked up from the scroll she had been reviewing.<br>
&quot;Rhiannon... good morning.&quot;  A pause.  &quot;I've sent for tea... did you get a chance to read over that scroll? <br>
As Chiara had come to expect, seeing Rhiannon's drive to succeed at her new responsibilities, the redhead nodded that she had.<br>
&quot;Good.  It mostly dealt with questions of recommended procedure when an unknown person was found on Amazon land.  Why do you think I had you, who is queen of domestic affairs, learn it?   <br>
&quot;Because as Queen of domestic affairs, I would probably be the most likely to be in or near the village if such an occasion arose. And since visitors would need to be dealt with quickly, whoever was closest would be the one to take care of it.&quot;<br>
Rhia, glad that Chiara had started her out with something she was confident about, waited for Chiara's answer. <br>
Chiara nodded.  &quot;Your answer is a good one.  In many cases, it would fall to you to see things were handled properly.&quot;  The queen paused, meeting her young sister's eyes.  &quot;The other central reason you must know such things is to know when standing orders have NOT been obeyed. Some circumstances may excuse that, but if that does not seem to be the case... you must ask yourself why an Amazon would deal violently with a person to be protected or allow a troublemaker to go.&quot; <br>
Rhia looks a little confused, but is taking it all in. The Shatomlics are a rather isolated tribe, so Rhia had never really learned from them how Amazons dealt with outsiders.<br>
She nods, waiting for Chiara to continue with the lesson.  <br>
Chiara sees the confusion, realizing she should have expected it of someone with Rhiannon's trusting nature.  She smiles, gently.<br>
&quot;Luckily, Amazons behave themselves for the most part.  We're trained to obey.&quot; <br>
The War Queen paused, before continuing. <br>
&quot;Right now, at least... I don't want you handling cases that you sense have a lot going on under the surface.  Those have a tendency to become dangerous.  Find some pretext to bring me into the discussion, and I'll guide you.  If I'm out of the village, stall until I return.  Can you think of a few ways to do that?&quot;   <br>
Rhia thinks for a moment and realizes that her first reaction would've been to say she needed to talk to Chiara, or to say that she needed more time to think about it. She dismisses these as being wrong, and tries to think of a right answer.<br>
&quot;I don't remember reading in any of the scrolls if there was a way to postpone a decision on a case.&quot; <br>
Chiara smiled.  &quot;I never said they were in the scrolls.&quot;  She clasped her hands together on top of the desk. <br>
&quot;The law gives the presiding queen a lot of discretion in determining how trials are run.  If you can find a point in the case that requires further proof - and there's always something - investigating that can take up time.  You can also say that you wish to spend some period of time in the temple in prayer and contemplation over the case, or if the timing is right that the trial should be postponed until the harvest is in, or a particularly large war party is in.  There's also the possibility of feigning illness, but I don't reccomend it.&quot;<br>
hia laughs. &quot;So it's okay to use lame excuses sometimes? I thought it would have to be a biggie..&quot;<br>
She creates imaginery scenarios in her head, picturing herself stalling for time with these methods <br>
&quot;No, not a 'biggie'... just be subtle.&quot;  Chiara reached for another scroll, and unrolled it, displaying a detailed map of their lands.  There are dots scattered across it, and a legend tying each color of dot to a prey animal.  &quot;This is this the hunting record so far this year...&quot;  She opens another scroll.  &quot;And, this is two years ago's.  What do you notice about these, Rhiannon?&quot;<br>
Rhia studies the two maps for a few moments.<br>
&quot;This area up here,&quot; she points to the map. &quot;is more heavily hunted than it was two years ago. If the hunting keeps increasing at this same rate, then in just a couple of years there will be almost nothing there to hunt.&quot; <br>
Chiara smiles like what she is - a teacher with a particularly bright pupil.  &quot;Exactly, Rhiannon. And, where would you shift the hunting to?&quot; <br>
&quot;Well...&quot; Rhia studies the map again. &quot;Right here, in this area where almost no hunting is done. &quot;<br>
Chiara nods.  &quot;Yes, some of the hunting could be shifted there.  But not all.  I've been to that area, and the tree cover is thin.  There's not as many large animals as one would guess, and the hunters would have to be particularly careful not to be seen or smelled. Where else?&quot;  She looks over to Rhia, awaiting an answer. <br>
Dori ran through the door to the council hall and slid to a halt right in front of the Queens, eyes wide open.  &quot;Oops.&quot;  She said, looking back over her shoulder, then back to the Queen, trying to catch her breath and getting ready for the fit she knew Chiara was about to throw. <br>
Rhia had just been about to speak when Dori ran in to the Hall.<br>
She noticed how fast the princess had run in and how heavily she was breathing and became concerned.<br>
&quot;Dori, are you alright?&quot; Rhia got up and put an arm around the other woman's shoulder, moving her to sit in the chair she's just vacated.<br>
&quot;What happened?&quot; <br>
Sitting down, Dori avoided looking at Chiara, getting her breath she looked up at Rhia instead, &quot;I'm fine my Queen.  I uh...we were...&quot;  she sighed knowing that Chiara had to be giving her the &quot;look&quot;.  Swallowing, &quot;I'm sorry I interrupted, my sisters and I were fooling around.&quot;  The dark haired princess looked down at her hands, feeling a tad bit ashamed.   <br>
&quot;Doriana, I understand needing to run off some energy,&quot; Chiara replied.  While not angry, her voice had a certain edge that did not bode well for the Princess.  &quot;But, since you have so much, maybe there's a more productive use for it.  Rhiannon and I were just discussing where to shift hunting to.&quot; <br>
Dori peeked up at Chiara and bit her lip, standing quickly, she said, &quot;Well then I guess I should let you get to it then.&quot;  She turned to head for the door, knowing it couldn't be that easy to get away. <br>
&quot;No...&quot;  Chiara said, silkily.  &quot;I'd like to get your impression on the issue.  You do spend more time out than I have been able to lately.&quot; <br>
Chiara knew she was being tough on Dori for a simple gaffe, but it was necessary if the young woman was going to be a great queen someday, as her mother had been.  And, it was Chiara's responsibility now to see that she did.   Dori stopped at Chiara's words and clenched her jaw, vowing to kill one pain in the butt best friend of hers.  Turning she looked back over at the queens and sighed.  She walked over to the map and studied it quietly.  Motioning to one area, &quot;We've over-extended ourselves here, and while this looks like a good area, there isn't enough forest to sustain animals, and over here, our borders aren't as secure as we'd like them.  So unless we want to add the extra danger of being picked off by our enemies while hunting, I'd say the best places are here...&quot;  She pointed near the long flowing river, then motioned to another area where their were grassy fields bordering dense forest, &quot;and here.  Give the other hunting ground time to replenish.&quot;  With that answer she looked up at Chiara and cocked a dark brow waiting for a response. <br>
